---
import ServicePage from "../layouts/ServicePage.astro";
import type { Faq } from "../data/faqs";

const faqs: Faq[] = [
  {
    question: "What does well pump replacement cost in the Upper Cumberland?",
    answer:
      "There is no honest flat answer. Pump type, horsepower, well depth, drop-pipe condition, wiring, pressure equipment and access all move the number. The responding provider quotes after evaluating the system.",
  },
  {
    question: "Should the pressure tank be replaced at the same time?",
    answer:
      "Sometimes providers recommend it when the tank is failing or badly undersized, because a bad tank shortens the life of a new pump. That call belongs to the provider after inspecting the tank, not to a rule of thumb.",
  },
  {
    question: "Can I just buy a pump myself and have someone drop it in?",
    answer:
      "Tennessee regulates pump installation, and matching pump capacity to the well and household demand matters for performance and pump life. Discuss equipment sourcing directly with the licensed provider.",
  },
];
---

<ServicePage
  title="Well Pump Replacement | Upper Cumberland TN"
  description="Request a well pump replacement evaluation in Cookeville and the Upper Cumberland, TN. Learn what drives the repair-versus-replace decision and what affects replacement scope."
  path="/well-pump-replacement/"
  h1="Well Pump Replacement in Upper Cumberland"
  crumbs={[
    { name: "Home", path: "/" },
    { name: "Well Pump Services", path: "/#services-heading" },
    { name: "Well Pump Replacement", path: "/well-pump-replacement/" },
  ]}
  defaultService="Well Pump Replacement"
  faqs={faqs}
  relatedLinks={[
    { label: "Well Pump Repair in Cookeville", href: "/well-pump-repair-cookeville-tn/" },
    { label: "Well Pump Installation", href: "/well-pump-installation/" },
    { label: "Pressure Tank Replacement", href: "/pressure-tank-replacement/" },
    { label: "Constant-Pressure Systems", href: "/constant-pressure-well-pump-systems/" },
    { label: "Tennessee Licensing Information", href: "/licensing-information/" },
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Every well pump eventually reaches the point where fixing it again stops making sense. Maybe
    it is the third service call in two years, maybe the motor finally shorted, or maybe the
    household outgrew what the pump was sized for twenty years ago. This page is for Upper
    Cumberland property owners weighing that decision — and for requesting an evaluation from an
    independent local provider who can look at the actual system.
  </p>

  <h2>Repair or Replace? The Factors That Matter</h2>
  <p>
    Age alone doesn't decide it. Providers typically weigh:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>What failed</strong> — a pressure switch or control box is routinely repairable; a burned-out submersible motor usually is not.</li>
    <li><strong>Failure history</strong> — repeated breakdowns shift the math toward replacement.</li>
    <li><strong>Repair cost versus replacement cost</strong> — pulling a deep submersible pump is labor-intensive either way, which can tilt the decision once the pump is out of the well.</li>
    <li><strong>System fit</strong> — a pump that never matched the well's yield or the property's demand may be worth replacing even if it still runs.</li>
    <li><strong>Well condition</strong> — a usable well with a bad pump needs a pump; a compromised well is a different conversation (see <a href="/water-well-drilling/">water well drilling</a>).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Submersible, Jet and Constant-Pressure Terminology</h2>
  <p>
    Most drilled wells in the region run <strong>submersible pumps</strong> — the motor and pump
    sit down in the well on a drop pipe. Shallower or older wells sometimes use
    <strong>jet pumps</strong> mounted above ground. Replacement is also the natural moment to ask
    about <a href="/constant-pressure-well-pump-systems/">constant-pressure systems</a>, which
    vary pump speed to hold steadier pressure. Which option fits depends on well depth, yield,
    electrical service and how the property uses water.
  </p>

  <h2>What Shapes the Scope of a Replacement</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Well depth and access</strong> — deeper pump settings mean more drop pipe, more wire and more pulling work.</li>
    <li><strong>Capacity and compatibility</strong> — the new pump must fit the well's yield and the household or farm demand; oversizing causes cycling, undersizing causes pressure complaints.</li>
    <li><strong>Pressure equipment</strong> — the tank, switch and controls are checked because they directly affect the new pump's lifespan.</li>
    <li><strong>Electrical condition</strong> — wiring, splices and the control box may need attention during the swap.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Requesting an Evaluation</h2>
  <p>
    Use the form on this page and choose "Well Pump Replacement." Include anything known about the
    system — pump type, well depth, service history — and describe the failure pattern. An
    independent provider evaluates the pump, controls, pressure system and well before
    recommending repair or replacement, and independently sets pricing and terms. Verify the
    provider's current Tennessee license on the
    <a href="/licensing-information/">licensing information page</a> before work begins.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
